Sometimes it’s the music that defines a trend. Take post-rock (which Asthmatic Kitty fans know just as well – or is that equally fine – as rock music). Kevin Smith once told some whiny filmmaker that if he was listening to the music because he thought it was “so cool”, he was in the wrong field. But without a brilliant score, there is no story. The two come together seamlessly in Don McGlashan’s tender yet biting songs for Heavenly. A stunningly powerful focus song, “You Are the One For Me”, provides a safe, jovial space for sliding intimacy back into a dialogue between two lovers, while opening track “Linger In Bed” marshals the horns in just the right places, until it’s time to chill out on the balcony, take in a well-tapped local and jot down some impressions in your diaries.

Now a veteran band core who knows the intricacies of the sound and what layers work best where, the mark has altered right along with merging generations. Or rather, the Mark is faithfully unaware. Probably because Mark isn’t listening to this. He’s still poking at the music in his takes, seeing what sounds right at what masse.
